fields.description:

https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/transforms

Transforms example of all parameters and data types:

{code:java}
array of object: {perspective: number}, ,object: {rotate: string}, ,object: {rotateX: string}, ,object: {rotateY: string}, ,object: {rotateZ: string}, ,object: {scale: number}, ,object: {scaleX: number}, ,object: {scaleY: number}, ,object: {translateX: number}, ,object: {translateY: number}, ,object: {skewX: string}, ,object: {skewY: string}
{code}


Support for the following parameters of Transform:
* perspective
* rotate
* rotateX
* rotateY
* rotateZ
* scale
* scaleX
* scaleY
* translateX
* translateY
* skewX
* skewY

Acceptance Criteria

fields.description:
After working on several text issues with React Native, our development team has expressed that the Engine's existing layout system is intended for after effects, and using that layout system for React Native is difficult, creates tech debt, and is confusing to understand and navigate.

The intent of this story is to better understand how to build an effective text layout system for React Native text. This set of work is crucial for any future development of the text system in React Native.

See the analysis done by the JSX Squad
https://youilabs.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/~514011514/pages/924188708/Text+Layout+in+React+Native?src=jira

fields.description:
*How would you like the feature to work? *
As a react-native developer, I would like to be able to specify base64 image in the source prop of an Image / ImageRef, as react-native supports it already.

[https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/images#uri-data-images|https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/images#uri-data-images]

*Why is this feature important to you?*
Using base64 image is very useful for very tiny images in order to prevent a network request from being emitted. Since most of our client's customer comes from a web background, they are familiar and used to work with base64 images.

In the case of SKY, they want to display a very small watermark on top of the player, and leverage this feature so they don't have to use a network request in order to render it. This use-case may be applied in other places throughout the application.

*Date/priority details if relevant*
Sorry it’s been twice I have been updating this because I am receiving different information.

This is launch gating, which is supposed to happen 6 weeks after customer trials has started. They aren’t in customer trial for now but, as you know, are aiming to start customer trials as soon as they can.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer targeting the cloud platform, I find it difficult to reason about creating custom UI controls for the player on that platform. It would be extremely useful if there was a sample demonstrating how this can be done. 

_Acceptance Criteria_

* Roku Cloud support only

At a minimum, the sample should demonstrate:

* How to make use of AE defined assets for player controls.
* How to export the player UI on top of the video surface.
* How to disable built-in Roku controller.

Basic features must include:

* After a remote control activation of the UI, it should show and automatically hide the controls after a few seconds.
* Demonstrate a "Play" / "Pause" button based on the playing status.
* Reflect the current playback time on the scrubber and on the scrubber control.
* Demonstrate how to connect play/pause/seek signals.
* Demonstrate how to populate the audio/CC track selection control.

fields.description:
This ticket is to support the stickyHeaderIndices on the ScrollView component, and for that prop to be inherited by VirtualizedList and FlatList.

*Acceptance Criteria:*
* stickyHeaderIndices is supported on ScrollView, FlatList, and VirtualizedList.
* This prop is supported across all platforms (Android, AndroidTV, AmazonFireTV, tvOS, iOS, Tizen, LG, PS4, UWP, Roku NDK, Roku Clould).
* Documentation is updated to reflect the change
* A testable sample is provided which demonstrates the functionality


*Possible Use Case:*

FlatList has callbacks for rendering:

* ListHeaderComponent
* ListEmptyComponent
* ListFooterComponent

It is possible freeze the header so it is always visible by adding the following prop/value to `<FlatList ... />`:

```
  <FlatList
    data={ this.state.FlatListItems }
    ItemSeparatorComponent = {this.FlatListItemSeparator}
    renderItem={({item}) => <Text style={styles.FlatList_Item} onPress={this.GetItem.bind(this, item.key)} > {item.key} </Text>}
    ListHeaderComponent={this.Render_FlatList_Sticky_header}
    stickyHeaderIndices={[0]}
/>
```

fields.description:
This ticket is meant to capture gaps between Cloud and other platforms. The work in these tickets is only required to be done on the Cloud platform.

The following components and props are required to meet acceptance criteria:

Animated APIs
* For Parity (CS-3512)
* Including the ability to stop animations (CS-3461)

Image Props
* For Parity (CS-3513)

Image Style Props
* For Parity (CS-3516)

Layout Style Props
* For Parity (CS-3517)

Stylesheet Props:
* For Partiy (CS-3518)

TouchableOpacity/TouchableHighlight
* For Parity (CS-3519)

Provided all props within this ticket all these components/modules will have 100% parity across platforms.

fields.description:
Currently in AE compositions, any text rendered is scaled accordingly based on the DPI of the device. This results in the following for a basic example:

 !Screen Shot 2019-07-16 at 1.37.37 PM.png|thumbnail! 

The desired output is to be similar to how Facebook RN does it, and how we plan to do it with device independent pixels in 5.6.

 !Screen Shot 2019-07-16 at 2.48.27 PM.png|thumbnail! 

You can see the desired output is for the font to be the same physical size regardless of device DPI.

fields.description:
As a cloud support agent, I want to see what network requests are made by a cloud app and when those requests succeed or fail.

Enabling better logging and trouble shooting will better support both our cloud DIY story AND our internal support teams ability to efficiently resolve issues.

fields.description:
This ticket is to determine the best way to provide concise samples surrounding key functionality so that React Native developers can see a sample and quickly understand what needs to be done to achieve the functionality of the sample.

The following use cases and rationale behind this product offering is outlined here: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FBZ-MnNnTkIXpFbT_z4NRw2uSkq5oUZAgE_ZM4dhOEU/edit?usp=sharing

The following use cases are areas of key functionality we believe is best demonstrate through an Enablement Sample (a sample that runs and can demonstrate functionality as if the end user was using this functionality):

* Navigation via deep linking
* Third-part library (build system support)
* Platform splash screens
* Profiling Tools
* Access to platform APIs
* Error Capture and Reporting
* Localization
* Gesture Support
* Automated Testing Support
* Screen Reader
* Remote Assets
* Mini Games

The following use cases are believed to be best demonstrated through documentation (e.g: code snippets, technical descriptions, articles, product documentation):
* Customize a sample or starting point when building a new You.i Engine React Native application
* Readings from platform specific input devices
* IAP
* Accessibility Settings
* Image Asset Compatibility
* Client Certificates for secure communication
* Cross platform web communication
* Clipboard support
* Navigation support via a software keyboard 
* Web browser
* Text To Speech
* Socket Communication
* Flexible date and time manipulation

The following use cases are believed to require investigations to determine whether or not they should be documentation or samples:
* Extending an application functionality via downloadable code (CodePush)
* Focus Navigation support via a hardware keyboard
* Software keyboard for text entry
* Word suggestions, spell/ grammar checking and word completion
* hardware keyboard for text entry
* third-party packaging support
* flexible bitmap format support
* Compatibility with UI independent third-party library/package utilization
* Compatibility with UI dependent third-part library/package utilization
* Ad frameworks (platform)
* Ad frameworks (webview)
* Text Scaling (accessibility)
* Remote ad content
* Application usage data
* Photo library and camera access
* Off-line interaction
* build dependency discovery

fields.description:
Android 10 has been launched for Pixel devices (Sept 3, 2019). Rollout to all devices will follow.

https://www.android.com/android-10/
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Android_10

Specific areas for investigation:
- new screen gesture system (support is mandatory)
- "bubbles" overlay notifications
- dark theme 
- storage system changes

Intention is:
- ensure that our current samples and apps work on the platform
- look for opportunities/functionality that could further enhance our offering

fields.description:
This ticket's purpose is to capture existing props that are not supported in the engine, and to track work against all remaining Image props/methods etc.

Below are props that do not have existing stories:
* abortPrefetch
* accesibilityLabel
* accessible
* blurRadius
* capInsets
* defaultSource
* fadeDuration
* loadingIndicatorSource
* onPartialLoad
* onProgress
* prefetch
* progressiveRenderingEnabled (.58 prop)
* getSize (on Cloud)
* resizeMethod
* resizeMode
* resolveAssetSource
* getSizeWithHeaders (.60 prop)

Requirements:
* All properties that can be supported (there may be platform or engine limitations, those should be marked as not possible to be supported in the JIRA ticket description or comments) are supported across all platforms (iOS, tvOS, OSX, UWP, PS4, Tizen, WebOS (if supported at the time), Android, AndroidTV, Amazon FireTV, Cloud).
* A way to validate these properties are working as intended, compared to Facebook's React Native behaviour.
* Documentation surrounding support is updated to reflect the new props/methods that are supported.

fields.description:
The youiengine should support and respect the Facebook RTL Layout support that comes with vanilla React Native as described here: https://facebook.github.io/react-native/blog/2016/08/19/right-to-left-support-for-react-native-apps

Currently the youiengine supports RTL aligned Text and TextRefs as well as RTL strings in these elements.  To fully support an RTL layout, this functionality should be extended to TextInput and TextInputRefs.  

This feature would allow apps build on the youiengine React Native platform to gain larger uptake in markets and locations internationally where RTL languages are used.

fields.description:
As described in the attached Cloud Self-Serve Deployment Epic (CS-2406), the purpose is to allow developers to deploy and manage stacks in different environments without the need for manual intervention to perform this operation.  Initially, developers would use a command line interface (CLI) perform the necessary operations for deployment.

Confluence Reference: https://youilabs.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/CLOUD/pages/735412338/Self-Serve+Deployment

Brands can deploy to dev and production stacks on demand based on Image Repo.  This repository would act as main interface between infrastructure and project teams. Once a project team has decided that a stack deployment is needed (prod / dev) then they can deploy images of a project to a predefined image repository. The image repository is reference by a build repository that contains detailed stack information needed for deployment.

High-Level Features:
Brands can push client and server builds to image repository
Deploy server builds to either Dev or Prod stacks
Brands would be able to sign client builds
Assistance from cloud team on best configuration options

Benefits:
Offload cloud team and helps support to deal with in market issue
Service teams want more options to deploy updates base on customer demand

fields.description:
The linked high-level Cloud Scaling Epic (CS-2884) describes areas of potential research and development to figure out ways to scale to millions of users while keeping infrastructure costs under control.  Currently, a single client must connect to a single You.i Engine running on a server in the cloud. Each server can support up to N number of engines running with M memory available on each server. As more clients use the service more servers are created to support the growing demand. The cost of each server varies depending on server configuration and the cloud provider. As costs grow, there becomes a break-even point in which infrastructure costs outweigh the cost to develop the application. This is cost prohibitive for our customers.

As part of this work, we must provide a reliable mechanism to process application events so that infrastructure can post-process the information. This is covered in the linked Event Handling Epic (CS-3133) - a dependency of Cloud Scaling.

fields.description:
Twitch would like to have access to the following hooks: applicationWillResignActive and applicationDidBecomeActive in the CYIAppLifeCycleBridge.

They are currently accessing it through the youilabsAppDelegate.mm on tvOS but wonder if it makes more sense to do so through the CYIAppLifeCycleBridge

Josh suggested: "We would probably need to do a spike to determine what platforms those are available to see if it makes sense to support as a cross platform feature."

Acceptance Criteria:
* Determine if this feature should be implemented as a cross-platform API or whether this should be a single platform feature
* Add support for applicationWillResignActive and applicationDidBecomeActive in the CYIAppLifeCycleBridge or in a way the is accessible for the specific platforms that are supported.
* Documentation on APIs added or changed to support the requested functionality.

* Measure current performance using above metrics these will be used as benchmarks for improving startup time
* Establish our target improvement (ex: 10% improvement)
* Start working to reach those targets

fields.description:
As of React Native 0.60.3, it’s possible to use the new Hermes JavaScript VM (https://github.com/facebook/hermes) with Android React Native apps. 

The Hermes VM uses significantly less space in the app than the previous VM, about 1.5MB vs. 10MB with the old one. Keeping the app size down is key for customer satisfaction and supporting our client teams' performance metrics.

Many React Native open source modules are also moving to it and may not ship releases that are backwards compatible.

fields.description:
The ticket is intended to capture all the requirements to provide the easiest integration of Chromecast into a You.i React Native application by a React Native developer.


Questions:
• What about the screen share functionality? https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromecast#Model_comparison
• What about different versions of chromecasts? https://support.google.com/chromecastbuiltin/answer/6059461?hl=en 
• How is this able to be done by a RN developer with the video component having limited extensibility?


Acceptance Criteria:
• Must work on all platforms that can support Chromecast (Cloud, Tizen, Android, AndroidTV, AmazonFireTV, iOS, tvOS, Roku)
• Documentation required on how to take an existing You.i React Native app and implement Chromecast within it - Potential for sample code to demonstrate the implementation.

fields.description:
This story can be split if needed. I think ideally we upgrade to the most recent stable version (as of right now, .59 is more stable, and .60 is very recent. However, it may be worthwhile to look at both).

.59 Potential Features
* React Hooks
* new JSC for android
* Inline requires on the metro bundler

Blog post: http://facebook.github.io/react-native/blog/2019/03/12/releasing-react-native-059

.60 Potential Features:
* AndroidX support
* Hermes JavaScript Engine for Android
* Removal of Webview and Geolocation
* CocoaPods
* Autolinking of packages

Changelog: https://github.com/react-native-community/releases/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md


Acceptance criteria:
* Stories are written by engineering which account for how they will upgrade from RN .58 to RN .59/.60
* Features in scope/out of scope are decided on before implementing the work to upgrade
* Areas of risk are identified before implementing the work to upgrade
* Upgrade is vetted by Tech Leads of each team

fields.description:
*How would you like the feature to work?*
As a react-native developer using youiengine, I want to be able to use third party libraries (i.e. Light Streamer) which leverages sub protocols web socket under the hood.

Currently the CYIWebSocket implementation doesn't support sub protocols (which are supported in native web socket implementation). 

*Why is this feature important*
SKY needs to be able to use the LightStreamer library, in order to deliver in app notification. This library uses websockets under the hood with sub protocols. Currently when using this library, we get a RSOD stating that sub protocols aren't supported.


*Date/priority details if relevant*
This is not launch gating, this is a feature to be dropped after launch. (update: as of July 29, this has been requested for launch)

fields.description:
*How would you like the feature to work?*

Currently the errors that are happening in the bluesky player implementation are mapped to _CYIAbstractVideoPlayer::PLAYBACK_ERROR_ error code, ignoring the native player initial error code. This causes a lack of information regarding the nature of the error. 



How we would like this to work, is being able to have the native player error code passed down the error event, so we can get more information regarding the original nature of the error.



This is only a proposal, but currently the _Error_ object is structured with an _errorCode_ (mapping to the abstract player error code enum) and a _message_ related to the error. Maybe we can have another field being _nativeErrorCode_ that would refer to the original error code from the native player.



*Why is this feature important to you?*

This feature is important in order to be aware of the original nature of the error. Currently, no matter the nature of the error, the error code is always the _PLAYBACK_ERROR_ code, from the AbstractVideoPlayer, which doesn't give much information about what happened.



Here is the native event in the Bluesky player with the list of errors 

https://developer.roku.com/en-gb/docs/references/brightscript/events/rovideoplayerevent.md#isrequestfailed-as-boolean





*Date/priority details if relevant*

SKY would like to have this being done at the same time that the other player features being worked on (live pause, bookmarking etc…).



*Why is this urgent?*

The urgency is around the ability to have all the information they need when an error happens on the user side, so they can react quickly and address the issue accordingly.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer building a Video Streaming application, I need to be able to know when seeking is completed. 

*Acceptance criteria:*
* Provide an RN developer a way to know when seeking has been completed.
* Provide a sample demonstrating how to know when seeking is completed.
* Updated documentation surrounding the adding prop/props.

*In the comments, Arcin provides an example of a prop that accomplish what is needed in react-video:*

https://github.com/react-native-community/react-native-video#onseek

*Below, Tom explains what is needed and a current workaround.*

The Video.seek() command should generate some kind of event to indicate that the seek is complete.

We are able to work around this by listening to current time updated events, however there is no way to know how much of a delay there is between the seek completing and the next time update.

The event should include the current time as part of the payload, as many video players will not do an exact seek for performance reasons, so once complete you need to know the actual position not the requested position.

fields.description:
On Peloton, the trickiest (and last remaining) crashes on Crashlytics are the ones without repro steps, reported by the public beta. We only have the stacktrace. 

I looked for the mentioned methods in uswish to get the location of the crash, and I often saw a {{YI_ASSERT}} on a shadow node there... but the variable is used just after in an unsafe way. I guess this is the cause of the crash but I can't be 100% sure.

We have 3 crashes where I highly suspect the shadow node to not have been found:

||Method||Crash||Source||Peloton ticket||
|dispatchViewManagerCommand| http://crashes.to/s/9591152e789 |[Source|https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/uswish/blob/5140c3ac045dc34fd0ff8f12e2bbe993885f58bc/react/react-native-youiengine/src/youireact/modules/UIManagerModule.cpp#L118]|[FIRE-2201|https://pelotoncycle.atlassian.net/browse/FIRE-2201]|
|DestroySubtree| http://crashes.to/s/5cccce297d8 |[Source|https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/uswish/blob/7506708bb04d2576ff0e4d62bb14a1b0ab891ab6/react/react-native-youiengine/src/youireact/nodes/ShadowRegistry.cpp#L61]|[FIRE-2212|https://pelotoncycle.atlassian.net/browse/FIRE-2212]|
|ClearFocusFromView| http://crashes.to/s/f885cc6e5f7 |[Source|https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/uswish/blob/d9aa98e092176de2501bcd7401d352c0a11e3302/react/react-native-youiengine/src/youireact/ShadowTree.cpp#L163]|[FIRE-2217|https://pelotoncycle.atlassian.net/browse/FIRE-2217]

*This ticket is not about fixing those crashes*, it is about having a better stacktrace in order to narrow down the issues.

I don't have access to the user's log file so I can't see the explicit {{YI_ASSERT}} message. There should be a way to display this message in the crash report as well. With this information in the report, we would be able to:
- Make sure the crash is caused by the instruction following the assertion
- Check if the crash is located everywhere (multiple tags) or on the specific part in the app (unique tags).
- If specific location, come up with repro steps quickly, saving hours of hazardous repro attempts...

I would suggest to add a macro in [YiError.h|https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/uswish/blob/develop/core/dist/include/utility/YiError.h] that also crashes in Release. 

Transferring the message with the tag value may not be easy. I think the only way is to call the Crashlytics context log API: https://docs.fabric.io/android/crashlytics/ndk.html#custom-logs-and-keys so the message will be attach to the crash in the dashboard. As Crashlytics is a 3rd-party dep, maybe we should just implement a hook (synchronous {{Signal}}?) before aborting, so each project would have a chance to handle the message like they want.

fields.description:
Sky wants the information from PauseBufferInfo exposed as a public API across platforms, we need to look at how best to design a public API for CYIAbstractVideoPlayer to expose the desired information, that can pull from available native APIs from all of the platforms we want to support.

As a reminder, these are the parameters we’re looking to expose, as described in Roku documentation found here.
https://developer.roku.com/en-gb/docs/references/scenegraph/media-playback-nodes/video.md#trickplay-fields
• pauseBufferStart (time): The beginning position of the video buffered when paused.
• pauseBufferEnd (time): The ending position of the video buffered when paused.
• pauseBufferOverflow (Boolean): Indicates that the video buffer was not able to save all video since being paused.
What these refer to, despite some confusion about the naming and descriptions, is the available range that can be seeked to on the live stream server. We also implemented a flag called isValid, which would remain false, until a pause buffer event is received for the first time, and then be set to true, because at least one valid pause buffer has been found.

fields.description:
This is based on the initial spike from CS-2702.  In the past, applications were limited to only 2 fonts that can be included for apps.  In addition, our cloud API for fonts was very restrictive in the sense that only certain font styles must be supported (i.e. setRokuBoldFont, setRokuRegularFont)

After further investigation, it should be possible to allow app developers to use more fonts, the exact number to be determined, and remove the cloud API for setting Roku Text.  One caveat, the font file names should be the same on the client and the server and using the following naming convention *fontName-fontStyle* (TBC).

One interesting aspect worth considering is the number of font sizes to include as part of the app.  Based on CS-2702, we discovered that a very small percentage of texture memory is used for each font size, approx. 0.3% for each font size.  This is not a significant amount if we consider 10 different font sizes would take up just 3% of the texture memory.

h2. Activities
- Provide a new API to set font based on a specific font naming convention
- Remove/deprecate old font API (make sure this is documented)
- Our existing build infrastructure should be able to account for new & different fonts 
- Confirm the maximum number of fonts to allow (document).  Confirm what happens when max+1 fonts are used (i.e. which font falls out)
- Upgrading apps should still function correctly, assuming client changes and API changes are updated

h2. Testing
- Verify that apps deployed both locally and in the cloud that new and different fonts are shown as expected
- Verify previous apps upgrading to this new approach functions as expected
- Verify max and max + 1 limit of fonts works as expected.

fields.description:
Some use cases demand to change the AE asset locator for the app to display different look and feel.

Currently:

* Layout and timeline files are translated into Roku scenegraph and can be loaded, however, associated png (static images) can only be accessed by server instance of the engine, not on the Roku client, so server instance shows the image as expected, but Roku client will not be able to display the image.
* Static assets need to be packaged together or full accessible URL starting with http(s) need to be provided to download. In this situation, the server app doesn't have an easy way to work with the remote assets.
* Our Roku cloud solution assumes that all assets are located in AWS S3 bucket, but our solution does not allow deviating from this location.

To improve the situation, the server app should respect the asset location change and serve the assets from there for scene export. This should allow access to other remote locations.

*Acceptance Criteria*

* Roku Cloud solution to support remote assets: to retrieve timeline/layout and an associated static .png file, and insert it into the screen

* Should provide a sample on how to setup and use the Bitmovin player on all supported platforms.

fields.description:
This story is about implementing support for a Progress Bar component and it's properties.

Reference:
https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/progressbarandroid
https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/progressviewios

*Component Properties*
* animating
* indeterminate
* progress
* testID
* progressImage
* progressTintColor
* progressViewStyle
* trackImage
* trackTintColor

*Acceptance Criteria*
* We are not supporting the component and style properties that have been struck out.
* This component must support the AE workflow and use design and animations built within it (the ref version).
* The non-ref version must support theming work done as part of RN-367 . (See images provided below).

fields.description:
Product Management story to contain all the work already described in the epic US-8442.

The goal of this story is to be able to use border props directly on views other than the <View> component. Currently, if a React Native developer wants to use the props below they must wrap their components in a <View> and specify the props there; this is quite unintuitive for a React Native developer.

The following props should be supported:
- borderRightColor
- borderBottomColor
- borderBottomWidth
- borderColor
- borderEndColor
- borderLeftColor
- borderLeftWidth
- borderRadius
- borderRightWidth
- borderStartColor
- borderTopColor
- borderTopWidth
- borderWidth

The following Views should be able to use the props above:
* ScrollView
* FlatList
* SectionList
* VirtualizedList
* TextInput
* Button (This is not clear?)

The <Image> component has a subset of styles that can be applied. To satisfy the requirements for Border Style on Images, the following props should be supported:
* borderWidth
* borderColor

These items must be supported on all platforms (iOS, tvOS, Android mobile, AndroidTV, AmazonFireTV, Roku NDK, Roku Cloud, LG, Tizen, PS4, UWP).

* ActivityIndicator must be in accordance with the designs laid out in RN-367 (See attached images for reference)

fields.description:
Currently, React Native developers have to write their own focus systems when building a React Native app, since the framework does not provide one out of the box. On the other hand, You.i Engine has a default focus system that will override and JS written focus engine.

Problem: When a client has selected React Native as their mobile and web strategy, and want to extend their current application to 10ft platforms using You.i React Native, they will need to rewrite their existing focus system to align with the default You.i Engine's focus system.

Ideal outcome: You.i React Native can support JS focus engines and the default You.i Engine Focus system can be opted out of, instead of enforced with no alternative.

Questions:
* Where are places where the opting out of the Engine focus system causes issues?
* How does this work with Cloud? Would they need do anything to accommodate this?

Included: Code Snippets from TBSTNT's custom focus engine.

fields.description:
This story is intended to capture the work required to port RN to LG.

Acceptance Criteria:

* The port is complete if all required functionality from the library is available. (Full regression of RN on LG, documenting an known issues with the platform)
* The appropriate build files have been created/updated
* Platform must be building on package
* Readme on how to build the project is updated
* Regression completed by test
* Result will be evaluated by product management to determine if it is fit for product release



Note: this story does not guarantee specific performance characteristics. After PM evaluation, additional stories may be needed to alter the software stack if performance is not acceptable.

fields.description:
PanResponder reconciles several touches into a single gesture. It makes single-touch gestures resilient to extra touches, and can be used to recognize simple multi-touch gestures.

By default, PanResponder holds an InteractionManager handle to block long-running JS events from interrupting active gestures.

*Research Spike Results*
* Pan Responder can already be used although it does not behave well
* Poor behaviour is caused by the way we are transforming our engine's action events into js touch events, specific issues will be noted in the comments

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Pan Responder works with touch and mouse events
* No regressions introduced in touch and mouse event handling
* Pan Responder and other event tests behave comparably in a vanilla app and a you.i engine app

fields.description:
Main story around the RN team side of the RN List Performance Squad work. All investigations, actions, and feature work pertaining to improving RN list performance within the RN team's domain are encapsulated by this main story.

*Acceptance Criteria - TBD*
Currently the Performance Team is working on creating the baseline performance metrics and goals that we will be working towards and use as the acceptance criteria for this task.

In the meantime the RN team is going to work towards improving the current RN list performance, regardless of the target goals not being established yet.

We have highlighted a number of areas and possible approaches to research, investigate and implement to improve our list performance. These tasks will be handled as sub-stories of this main task.

fields.description:
This story is about implementing support for the Modal component and its properties.

Reference: https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/modal.html

*Considerations*
* An enhanced, animated, and customizable React Native modal: https://github.com/react-native-community/react-native-modal

*Component Properties*
* visible
* -supportedOrientations-
* onRequestClose
* onShow
* transparent
* animationType
* -hardwareAccelerated-
* onDismiss (back button support)
* -onOrientationChange-
* -presentationStyle-
* animated

*Acceptance Criteria*
* We are not supporting the component and style properties that have been struck out.
*  Must work on all RN supported platforms (Cloud, Tizen, PS4, UWP, iOS, tvOS, Android, AndroidTV, AmazonFire TV, Roku NDK)

fields.description:
This story is intended to capture the use of the Animated.event() with useNativeDriver set to true.

In 5.4, we released the ability to use Native Animations with Animated.decay(), Animated.timing(), and Animated.spring(), and providing Animated.event() would give us 100% Native Animation coverage on all the Animated methods.

Acceptance Criteria:
* Support for the Animated.event() method's use with useNativeDriver
* Updated documentation around Native Animation support
* A way to test the Native animations and information to help testers know what they are testing

fields.description:
As a designer, I want to make uses of Drop Shadows in my design. As a React Native Developer, I will need to be able to accomplish drop shadows as they are used in designs.

Acceptance Criteria:
* Support for the shadowColor, shadowOffset, shadowOpacity, and shadowRadius props of the Shadow Props Style.
* Support for each component which can use View Style Props or Shadow Props (ScrollView, FlatList, VirtualizedList, Image, SafeAreaView, TextInput) -- Not 100% sure I got all of the supported components
* Tests which demonstrate the use of these props
* Updated documentation on their support


*Below is a use case provided by Travis:*
In the preliminary design DTV Now as sent, they incorporate a sublet drop shows.

 !image-2019-05-30-09-05-22-976.png|thumbnail! 
 !image-2019-05-30-09-06-45-467.png|thumbnail! 

They may have the intention of using css styles to create that shadow, which vanilla RN supports.

fields.description:
ScrollView's contentContainerStyle was seen to be used frequently in an existing React Native app, we are evaluating. After looking at the supported components and module spreadsheet this had been indicated as supported partially by Cloud and not supported by other platforms. After further investigation, we thought we should put both to "Not Supported".

This ticket is intended to capture all the work to support the contentContainerStyle on the ScrollView Component which would also apply to VirtualizedList and FlatList. The property sets the styles that will be applied to the scroll view content container which wraps all of the child views.

https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/scrollview#contentcontainerstyle

Both Flatlist and VirtualizedList support ScrollView props.
https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/flatlist#props
https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/virtualizedlist#props

Questions:
* Would this be dynamically supported (would changing style dynamically update the UI?)

fields.description:
As a React Native developer responsible for implementing screen reader functionality for my application, I need support for React Native's related functionality.

A screen reader is a form of assistive technology that attempt to convey what people with normal eyesight see on a display to their users via non-visual means, like text-to-speech. They do this by applying a wide variety of techniques that include for example interacting with dedicated accessibility APIs, and using various operating system features.

Clients has asked us to provide estimates around screen reader support within React Native. The final solution must support all platforms, but a priority order is listed below:

# Apple TV
# PlayStation 4
# iOS
# Android / Amazon Fire TV
# BlueSky
# Xbox One
# Samsung Tizen
# X1 (TBD)

*Key Documents*

[Product Requirements: Accessibility|https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-dxuCHMdbOPXB8_vM-D-3BPGDwzjq7Qr5WViMjyKKaw/edit?usp=sharing] 

[Product Accessibility Initiative|https://drive.google.com/file/d/1VndbY5xGRPqyUcrfoC0g5aQeptkw47ni/view?usp=sharing]

*Acceptance Criteria*

* Support for screen reader (TalkBack on Android, and VoiceOver on iOS and tvOS) and associated functionality via the {{Accessibility}} API in React Naive: [https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/accessibility|https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/accessibility] 
* A means to check if the screen reader is currently active. Note that React Native already provides an API through the {{AccessibilityInfo}} module.
* Feature should include TTS solution for missing platforms.
* A means to supply Accessibility related properties and actions to After Effects UI components, including relevant View functionality that allows for screen reading functionality work.
* A means to supply Accessibility string content in different languages.
* 10-foot support around Accessibility related properties, such as tap, magic tap, or escape, for example.

fields.description:
As a video stack developer, I would like the ability to use a JavaScript video player that supports an MSE/EME video player stack. The ask around this feature is for the You.i Engine One SDK to support the ability to use a JavaScript video player (compatibility with), but not to provide an end-to-end solution, at this point in time. The work needed on the SDK side is to enable access to an iframe running within a browser context.

*Acceptance Criteria*

* Application developer must be able to use an MSE/EME player or a native platform player, depending on the platform

fields.description:
Currently our oldest supported version of Android is 7.0 (API level 24). This is quite high, and only supports [58% of devices in market|https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards].

The original rationale for supporting this version is to match "Google's minimum supported version". However, this may be a misinterpretation of the minimum target SDK, which has no bearing on the minimum SDK version.

See:
https://developer.android.com/training/basics/supporting-devices/platforms#sdk-versions and
https://support.google.com/googleplay/android-developer/answer/113469#targetsdk

Google also supports older versions through their [Support Library|https://developer.android.com/topic/libraries/support-library].

Flutter, a Google cross platform framework similar to ours, supports at minimum Android 4.1 (API level 16).

We should be supporting a lower minimum version of Android to increase our supported device percentage.

[Slack conversation context|https://youilabs.slack.com/archives/C42PH1B0F/p1560433990004900] (and [ensuing thread|https://youilabs.slack.com/archives/C42PH1B0F/p1560434061005300]).

fields.description:
This work has been split from PM-46.

This ticket is about support SDK specific file extensions e.g. : identifier.platform.SDK.js. So that in the event that a user wants to use the You.i Engine SDK on iOS, they would be able to specify to use the Youi SDK on iOS (by using a {{pdp.ios.youi.js}}, while still being able to use Facebook's Android version (by using {{pdp.android.facebook.js}}, or just not specifying and SDK as in pdp.android.js).

This set of work should only be contained to the SDK part of the format of identifier.platform.SDK.js while PM-46 is about only support the platform specific extension of the format identifier.platform.SDK.js.

Acceptance criteria:
* Must support all platform/SDK combinations
* Must provide technical documentation around this capability and use cases around how to leverage it.
*

fields.description:
This story is a result of the performance investigations.

Using https://github.com/maicki/why-did-you-update we discovered that vanilla react components trigger unnecessary rerenders. We should wrap the components in a PureComponent.

This will be an improvement to facebook's react native, which would require users to import those components directly from our package to receive those performance improvements. Wrapping the components will also be the first step in providing additional functionality to react native that is only available in our engine.

This will create additional nodes in the tree.

fields.description:
This ticket is intended to capture the support of resizeMode prop on the Image component. (https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/image#resizemode).

Acceptance Criteria:
* Prop is supported on the image component on all supported platforms (Android, AndroidTV, AmazonFireTV, iOS, tvOS, Tizen, LG, PS4, Xbox, Roku NDK, Cloud).
* Documentation is updated to reflect support.

Below is examples provided by services teams working on client's projects. It outlines the code used and their expectation (along with vanilla react native's behaviour vs the engine's behaviour).

<Image
     source={{uri: 'https://i.ibb.co/3TC5KLF/Scroll-View-Top-Gradient.png'}}
     resizeMode='repeat'
     style={{
            width: '100%',
            height: 48,
            position: 'absolute',
            top: 0,
          }}
/>

The above code renders the gradient as a black solid in the You.i RN product.
 !image (3).png|thumbnail! 

In vanilla RN it renders like this:
 !image (4).png|thumbnail! 

And our documentation states that resizeMode as a prop is partially supported. 
https://developer.youi.tv/5.2/Content/RNsupportedComponents/VanillaSuppCompsLists.htm?Highlight=image#Image
 !Screen Shot 2019-06-04 at 9.06.58 AM.png|thumbnail! 

Ellation has brought up that the resizeMode prop does not seem to be working as it does in vanilla RN.

Also here is a local copy of the gradient used in the code:
 !Scroll-View-Top-Gradient.png|thumbnail!

fields.description:
In order to compare with our internal TwitchPlayer, we need information about the current stream. 
DecodedFrames should contain the number of video frames that have been decoded so far. 
RenderedFrames should contain the number of video frames that have been sent to be rendered (to a texture) 
DroppedFrames should contain the number of video frames that we have not rendered.

DecodedFrames should always be >= RenderedFrames + DroppedFrames 
DecodedFrames will be a little bit higher than the sum of RenderedFrames and DroppedFrames due to temporal frames.

These 3 numbers must be reset when loading a new stream.

----- original message -----
Look at platform capability to determine if these stats are exposed and can be integrated into You.i SDK, otherwise this is platform limitation.
To be investigated by Product team.

~* Please see Zendesk Support tab for further comments and attachments.~

fields.description:
This is different from the CYIAbstractVideoPlayer::BufferingStarted and CYIAbstractVideoPlayer::BufferingEnded event.

This event should only be sent for buffering caused by lack of bandwidth.

1) If you just started a video through 'CYIAbstractVideoPlayer::Load', then OnRebuffering must *not* be called. 
2) If you seek to a different position in a video, then OnRebuffering must *not* be called.
3) If you switch quality (through SetQuality) and this causes a small buffering to occur (due to internal seek), then OnRebuffering must *not* be called.

Basically, OnRebuffering should only be called when Buffering occurs during the Playing state unexpectedly due to a sudden lack of bandwidth.

~* Please see Zendesk Support tab for further comments and attachments.~

fields.description:
This is needed for A/B testing the players.

When CYIAbstractVideoPlayer::Seek() is called, the player will seek. 
Once the seek is completed and playback has resumed, the signal SeekEnded should be called. 
You can also implement the SeekStarted as well.

The signature can be similar to the BufferingStarted/BufferingEnded signals.

Ideally, SeekStarted/SeekEnded will only be called on a user initiated Seek. So this means that if a seek is being performed due to quality change, then SeekStarted/SeekEnded should *not* be called.

An alternative implementation can also always call SeekStarted/SeekEnded but also provide a reason for the seeking (user initiated, quality change, internal error, etc.)

~* Please see Zendesk Support tab for further comments and attachments.~

fields.description:

fields.description:
In order to A/B test the platform player with the Twitch player, the following feature needs to be added to CYIAbstractVideoPlayer 
* GetBandwidthEstimate

The signature can look like this:

This would return the estimated bandwidth the player has. This is different from the steam kbps 
or from the current quality kpbs, but this is really the bandwidth estimated from the player 
point of view.

Our internal player returns the bandwidth in bps, but to be consistent with the rest of the CYIAbstractVideoPlayer interface, it should return it as a float in kpbs instead.

/** @return for network streams the current ABR bandwidth estimate in kpbs or -1.0 if unknown */ 
virtual float CYIAbstractVideoPlayer::GetBandwidthEstimate() const = 0;

fields.description:
PS4 support on Engine One is noted as being BETA level in our current Engine release.
*Engine One version 5.1 will be released with RN on PS4 in a BETA state.Development of PS4 applications, using the RN framework will be possible.NOTE: Without a performant JS executor it will not be possible to release aPS4 application to market.*

Though we pinned our hopes on an updated and more performant executer, subsequent performance improvement work has been done and anecdotal evidence states that performance is not as compromised as it was when we initially reviewed it.

This story requests that we build two-three applications on PS4 against the latest Engine release.
1. RNSample app
2. Auryn
3. Redbox, A&E, or SKY (existing RN apps that are currently not available on PS4)

Reviewing the performance of these applications will allow us to remove the BETA designation if performance has improved to a market acceptable level.

fields.description:
When building for a 10foot platform, often a different animation for Press and Focus are desired on an element. A screenshot is provided to show the desired states of a themed Button Component. 

 !57077399-f6fc7300-6cb9-11e9-9427-8f5bbb21dc5b.png|thumbnail! 

Although there doesn't seem to be a way to trigger an onPress event when a button already has Focus.

I've attempted to workaround this issue in a couple different methods: 
1. Using prop `isTVSelectable` on a `Animated.View`
  - this method allows us to call an animation / function when onFocus and onBlur events are fired
  - this method has no ability to to trigger the onPress, onPressIn, and onPressOut events

2. Using TouchableOpacity
  - this method allows us to call an animation / function when the button receives focus although it consumes the onPressIn and onPressOut events rather than onFocus and onBlur, preventing me from providing a different animation for the focus and press states

3. Using TouchableWithoutFeedback wrapped inside an Animated.View with prop isTVSelectable
 - This method allows me to call an animation / function when the Animated.View receives focus, and allows me to call an animation / function when the TouchableWithoutFeedback is pressed. Although this does not work well with TV platforms.
 - When using a TV remote there is no way of triggering the onPress events

I have an open PR here for Reference using method #3 from above, for trying to achieve these animations: https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/react-native-public-modules/pull/83

I've written up a quick test to show the behaviour and recorded it here [^AnimatedBehaviour-cut.mov] 
- Context for the video, each button has an animation for Focus In/Out and Press/Release
- The Focus animations scales the button up to 110%, the Press Animations Scales the button down to 50%

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I need support for creating and building native modules, such as CMake targets, include directories, library paths, etc., so that existing C++ libraries or applications can produce native modules as a build artefact that can then be picked up by React Native projects and consumed.

This functionality can then be used to enable teams to easily reuse some of their existing functionality in their RN efforts.

*References*
https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/uswish/blob/develop/react/react-native-youiengine/src/youireact/NativeModule.h
https://stackoverflow.com/c/youi-tv/questions/1507/1574#1574

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Appropriate build variables so that developers can more easily create RN native modules
* Options for packaging the native module into a Node.js package

fields.description:
As an RN developer, I need access to the tags used in video streams for supporting higher level features such as ads, black outs, or even meta-data communication from the back-end to the application. This feature is about exposing the tags found in manifests and stream data so that application developers can trap and respond to them as needed.

*Technical Details (provided by development team)*
The RN API would be modified to expose the onTimedMetadata prop on the Video and VideoRef components. This is a callback function that is called each time the underlying video player encounters a timed metadata tag in the video stream. The function's payload is a single blob that contains whatever metadata found in the timed metadata tag (ID3, MPEG-DASH events, SCTE-35, etc). It is up to the client application to parse the payload.

h3. References

* React-Native-Video onTimedMetadata prop: [https://github.com/react-native-community/react-native-video#ontimedmetadata|https://github.com/react-native-community/react-native-video#ontimedmetadata]
* Using Timed Metadata: [https://www.unified-streaming.com/blog/how-make-your-media-streams-smarter-using-timed-metadata|https://www.unified-streaming.com/blog/how-make-your-media-streams-smarter-using-timed-metadata]

*Acceptance Criteria*

* Solution must allow client to capture any desired meta-data on the available stream (unfiltered, if possible)

fields.description:
The main goal of the JSX initiative is: The ability for React Native developer to develop and release a video playback application using only JSX for the UI, across all platforms supported by You.i Engine One

* As a React Native developer, I want to use an SDK to build 10ft applications.
 
* As a React Native developer, I want to use same tools and strategies that I use when developing video playback applications for iOS, Android, and Web, so that I can be just as productive  when using You.i Engine One as when using React Native.
 
* As a React Native developer, I want to experience the least amount of fragmentation when developing across all platforms the You.i Engine One supports so that React Native developers don’t need to have platform specific expertise to build applications when using You.i Engine One.
 
* As a React Native developer I want to be able to evaluate You.i Engine One by building screens and proof of concept applications using only JSX.

fields.description:
The Services Team has been building a collection of modules inspired by some of our engagements.

This has, however, demonstrated a need for a tool that links native modules built for engine against the client side code.

We have built it as part of the modules project, but really this should be part of the youi-tv cli as as subcommand, eg; `youi-tv link <path-to-module>`. This can be used in conjunction with any non-youi developed modules as well and should not be specific to the modules in this repository.

Here is a link to the current implementation:
https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/react-native-public-modules/tree/master/youi-link-cli

fields.description:
*How would you like the feature to work?* 
As a React Native developer creating a custom native module around video playback, I find current options for preparing video playback to be too limited. The _CYIAbstractPlayer::Prepare()_ method doesn't offer the option of specifying a starting position for the playback. The only way to execute this is to change the initial playback state to PAUSED, call the _seek()_ method once the media is ready, and initiate playback with the _play()_ method.

The client has a bookmarking feature, and would like to be able, through the _Prepare()_ method, to specify the starting position of the playback.

*Why is this feature important to you?*
- Align their implementation onto their current in-market app which uses BrightScript and allow them to start the playback to a specific position.
- Prevent a loss of playback time due to the wait required for the MEDIA_READY state.

*Date/priority details if relevant*
They can go with the offered solution for now (using _seek()_) but this is something they are looking to be available in the short term.

fields.description:
The most accessible fonts for rendering emoticons are typically colored emoticon fonts. An example of one can be found here: https://www.google.com/get/noto/#emoji-zsye-color

Our current version of freetype (2.4.10) does not support loading these fonts. This makes it unnecessarily difficult to find a font that supports emoticons.

Freetype 2.5 supports loading color emoticon fonts.

fields.description:
Currently `getCurrentFocus()` method and `ViewWithFocusChanged` signal are exposed through the YIFocusEngine C++ API.   Having this API extended to our React Native solution is needed.  
Initial thoughts were  `getCurrentFocus()` should return the currently focused component or its ref. and `ViewWithFocusChanged` should be triggered when focus has changed within the focusEnigne/FocusManager.



*SKY use case*
I am going to explain the use case for sky driving this feature request.

They want to implement a left-hand side drawer menu. On the home screen, they have a list of list (called rails). The drawer should only be openable when an item in the first rail is focused. Due to the nested nature of those rails and the requirement for the drawer to be hosted way higher in the component hierarchy, the only option available currently is to keep track of the focused elements at the top component, by bubbling up the tree the focused state of the rails items using props. This becomes quickly hard to maintain and manage, as well as goes against the react concept of driving data top-to-bottom.

Current possibilities are :
- Having a way to know what is the current focus
- Implementing a custom native module to keep track of the availability of the drawer menu, removing the need to drive data bottom-to-top

fields.description:
Sky has added an imperative call for prepare and they are not using the source prop on `Video` or `VideoRef`. Because of the asyncronous nature of how compositions are loaded, they cannot rely on `ComponendDidMount` to know that the video ref is ready.

I suggested using an `OnLoad` or `ref` prop, but apparently this was not sufficient. I then suggesting setting the composition to load synchronously, which seems to be working for them.

The request is a callback prop (onLoad for example) that indicates the player is ready to use.

fields.description:
*Scenario*
SKY is integrating conviva in their solution and need to communicate bitrate changes to the conviva sdk. In order to do that, they are subscribing to _onCurrentTimeUpdated_ event, calling _getPlayerStatistics()_ from it and comparing previous / current bitrate value to detect a change.

*Ask*
The request is to be able to subscribe to a _onBitrateChange_ event directly on the *VideoRef* to remove that manual comparison step.

fields.description:
This is a BLOCKING feature for DTV NOW adoption of the You.i engine.  They require an implementation asap.

Widevine has the ability to add data to body of a POST request when communicating with the license server. However, we do not expose this capability in our API. This can be a blocking issue for customers who rely on this as part of their DRM flow.

Currently this ability is exposed for PlayReady.

Where to inject data:

ExoPlayer
AVPlay (see setDrm and AVPlayDrmOperation)

Areas with missing functionality:

YiExoPlayerVideoPlayer.cpp
CYIExoPlayer.java

fields.description:
Client came across this post:

https://stackoverflow.com/c/youi-tv/questions/3267

And is now requesting support for PATCH, as their API requires it.

Here is their initial request:

{code:java}
Hello,

I am trying to make a network request using the PATCH method, but that seems to not be supported as the request fails due to "Bad Parameters". I am making the request via JS. Are PATCH network requests not supported? If this is a bug, when can we expect this to be fixed?

NOTE: If we switch from PATCH to POST the network request goes through (doesn't error out) but it is not what we need.

Sample errors below:

=============================================================================================

let promise = fetch(req.url, fetchOptions)

1. POST, it works, request is sent

'https://dev-access-api.ea.com/userSettings?cmsStage=publish&device=console&locale=en-us&marketplaceid=en-us&platform=playstation-4', { compress: true, 
method: 'POST', 
headers: 
{ Accept: 'application/json', 
'Content-Length': '26', 
'Content-Type': 'application/json' }, 
body: '{"sharing":false}', 
redirect: 'follow', 
mode: 'cors', 
credentials: 'include' }

D/CYIHTTPService: Process: 2 transfers running (1 queued requests) 
D/CYITransferHandle: Request Url(https://dev-access-api.ea.com/userSettings?cmsStage=publish&device=console&locale=en-us&marketplaceid=en-us&platform=playstation-4) 
D/Transfer: REQUEST: https://dev-access-api.ea.com/userSettings?cmsStage=publish&device=console&locale=en-us&marketplaceid=en-us&platform=playstation-4 
D/CYIHTTPResponse: Parsing HTTP response header for https://dev-access-api.ea.com/userSettings?cmsStage=publish&device=console&locale=en-us&marketplaceid=en-us&platform=playstation-4: 
HTTP/1.1 403 Forbidden 
Server: AkamaiGHost

2. Patch, it doesnt work, error throw from Youi. Request not sent out.

'https://dev-access-api.ea.com/userSettings?cmsStage=publish&device=console&locale=en-us&marketplaceid=en-us&platform=playstation-4', { compress: true, 
method: 'PATCH', 
headers: 
{ Accept: 'application/json', 
'Content-Length': '26', 
'Content-Type': 'application/json' }, 
body: '{"sharing":false}', 
redirect: 'follow', 
mode: 'cors', 
credentials: 'include' }

W/MakeMethod_N2yi5react16NetworkingModuleE: Failed to process args for native module N2yi5react16NetworkingModuleE method sendRequest()! 
W/NativeModuleBase: Bad arguments passed to method 'sendRequest': 
#0: failed 
=============================================================================================

Thanks, 
Stanislav
{code}

fields.description:
As a React Native developer requesting video or making web API calls. I often have the need to add headers to my HTTP request. This broad capability can be useful for a variety of use cases which involve adding one or more headers to a web API request.

When requesting video:

{code:javascript}source={{  uri: "https://www.example.com/video.mp4",  headers: {    Authorization: 'bearer some-token-value',    'X-Custom-Header': 'some value'  }}}{code}

And via general requests by adding to the header:

{code}<Image  source={{    uri: 'https://facebook.github.io/react/logo-og.png',    method: 'POST',    headers: {      Pragma: 'no-cache',    },    body: 'Your Body goes here',  }}  style={{width: 400, height: 400}}/>{code}


The video related headers will need them propagated to the segment / manifest requests made the platform platform. This capability may vary by platform.

_Acceptance Criteria_

* Should be made available on every platform; exceptions should be raised.
* Platform player exceptions that do not support the ability propagate headers to segment / manifest requests should be documented.

fields.description:
There are a few cases where doing text layout can be expensive

* Long paragraph text box
* Text with ellipse

Tested on Android Nvidia shield, depends on the length (in debug) it can take upto 100ms to do so.
This drives down the FPS (drive up update time) significantly.

In the attachment you can see the time spend for TextLayout.

Suggestion:
- compute Text Layout in the background thread.

fields.description:
All of our Ref components support a few props that are very useful but are not available in non-Ref components. A few come to mind:
* visible
* focusable
* onCompositionDidLoad (or whatever the name will be, see RN-1679)
* hasTVPreferredFocus - Listed in our docs as tvOS only - not sure if it's correct or not
* onFocusInDescendants and onBlurInDescendants on the Flat List component (Ellation)

Setting initial focus on a Touchable* has to be done after the first render, while onCompositionDidLoad allows you to do it during the first render, leading to two different ways to work with FocusManager.

Visible is very useful in helping reduce overdraw on items that are out of view, or below other objects. It also disables focus, making it valuable in building a screen stack.

fields.description:
Add the ability to update and/or re-export individual list items.

Currently when anything in a list needs to be updated, the whole list needs to be re-exported. This can be expensive and unnecessary for large lists especially when multiple updates need to be done periodically.

A use case for this could be updating an "episode progress" view for each episode in a list of episodes. If progress for each episode needs to be retrieved individually, the episodes could be updated one by one with this feature. Without it, the only alternative would be waiting for progress for all episodes to be retrieved, then re-exporting the whole list afterwards.

fields.description:
This spike is to determine a technical path forward surrounding focus navigation when the TalkBack/VoiceOver accessibility feature is enabled on Android/iOS/tvOS.

If a focus solution cannot be found, then limitations surrounding the TalkBack/VoiceOver feature must be technically documented. Features that can help clients identify when the feature is being used, so that can report on the incompatibility to their users should be identified.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* One or more stories describing the work involved in supporting the TalkBack and VoiceOver feature. At this point, a containing feature will also be created.
* One of more stories describing the documentation needing to inform on the limitations, and the stories needed so that a mechanism can be provided so that users can identify that the feature has been enabled.

fields.description:
If an imageNode is size N x N, and when loading an image within it it ends up being N-M x N (Same height, but smaller width), it defaults to being left aligned within the imageNode.

It does not appear possible to change the alignment of the scaled image within the ImadeNode. (In this case i would like right alignment)

fields.description:
ZD-2889 - https://youitv.zendesk.com/agent/tickets/2889

A&E wants add "source map" to their crash report system.

currently, "source map" is generated during the building face, but is not being outputted.
Thus, they have to call it externally on a second time.

they request to output "source map" in the "bundlejs.rb"

more details in the email thread ZD-2889 - https://youitv.zendesk.com/agent/tickets/2889

fields.description:
If there is a crash in the native code outside of the js runtime, peloton wants to still see the javascript stacktrace where the js runtime was at the time of the crash, so they can fix native-side inmarket issues. 

We would need to hook into the `signal` handlers for sigsegv etc and access the js stacktrace to send to fabric on a crash, though we currently have no access to the current js stacktrace (if the runtime even exposes this?)

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I would like an easier way to bring in an existing Swift/Objective C/Java/C# functionality and bridge them into C++/JS.

At this time, it's undocumented and complicated to have these "just work". Getting these to build and run does require changes to the build scripts and intimate knowledge of the engine.

As an example, please see: https://stackoverflow.com/c/youi-tv/questions/3376 and https://stackoverflow.com/c/youi-tv/questions/1922.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* A reduction of the amount of boilerplate code required for Android
* Examples and documentation of native code per technology layer (Swift, Java).
* Documentation of required build changes needed to get the various native modules building

fields.description:
Squad effort to improve the performance of lists, screen transitions, and start up times. 

Primarily we are looking to:
* Define metrics that can be used to objectively measure our 'performance'. 
* Set target goals based on these metrics (perhaps by measuring the same metrics on vanilla RN implementations and our native implementation and supported platforms etc )
* Push to meet these performance goals by investigating performance improvements we could make in the areas our metrics show we are lacking in.

fields.description:
After discussion it has been decided that the easiest solution would be for You.I RN ListRefs to support a callback that will fire after initialScrollIndex has been applied. This callback should pass in the ref of the item that was scrolled to so that it can be used in FocusManager functions.

Below is the content from the original bug report that brought about this request:

//

We have a list which uses magnets. The aim is to onLoad scroll to the item that the user was last looking at and have it focused.

When using {code}onLoad={ref => ref && FocusManager.focus(ref)}{code} on the listItem itself, it appears we do not need to use {{initialScrollIndex}} or {{getItemLayout}} as the magnets cause the item to be scrolled to the right place when the focus event is fired.

However if the item would initially be off-screen before scrolling, the focus event fails to fire.

I believe the proper fix would be for the {{getItemLayout}} function to be applied before the {code}onLoad={ref => ref && FocusManager.focus(ref)}{code}. This would scroll the item in to view, and then the focus event could fire on it properly, but it seems like they happen at the same time.

This means if the item is visible before scrolling, it applies both the focus/magnet scroll AND the {{getItemLayout}} scroll and so ends up scrolling to the wrong item, but focusing the right one. If the item is not visible before scrolling, it scrolls to the right item but does not focus it.

For reference I have recreated this issue in RNSampleApp by adding magnets to the "List-Horizontal" ListRef:
{code}
          snapToInterval={0}
          snapToAlignment="start"
{code}
and changing the initial index that is being focused {code}index == 0 && this.props.firstList ? FocusManager.focus(ref) : {}{code} indexes 0 to 4 work, 5 and above do not work.

fields.description:
As a software developer or technical designer, I find the After Effects component library to be out of date and not aligned to how I need to work. The content of the component library should be renewed to address the following issues:

* antiquated techniques
* unsupported features
* unsupported platforms
* poor naming practices
* compatibility (RN vs. C++)

As a result, the component library should provide components for a variety of projects that are practical and extendable.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Must package the component panels separate from the plug-in so that a designer or developer can choose the component panel they want to use. If a default needs to be chosen, then the new component panel should be selected. Only one component panel package can be installed at the same time.
* Must include product documentation around the installation of the new / old package. It should include how to switch component panel packages, and any After Effects specific installation procedures.
* Technical documentation around how to use the new component panel. The old component panel documentation should be "deprecated" but remain publicly available.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I need support for the performance related properties the React team has added so that I can better tune my application. The properties have been listed below:

FlatList	getItemLayout: *Already supported for both RN and Cloud.*
FlatList	initialNumToRender: *Already supported for both RN and Cloud.*
FlatList	removeClippedSubviews
FlatList	viewabilityConfig
FlatList	       viewabilityConfigCallbackPairs *No Work Needed*
ScrollView	removeClippedSubviews
ScrollView	scrollEventThrottle: *Already supported on RN. Partial Support on CS (investigate limitations).*
SectionList	initialNumToRender *No Work Needed*
View	        removeClippedSubviews 
VirtualizedList        maxToRenderPerBatch: *Already supported on RN and Cloud.*
VirtualizedList  	onScrollToIndexFailed: *Already supported on RN and Cloud.*
VirtualizedList  	removeClippedSubviews 
VirtualizedList	        updateCellsBatchingPeriod: *Already supported on RN and Cloud*
VirtualizedList        windowSize *No Work Needed*

*Discuss*
View	        renderToHardwareTextureAndroid (generalized support possible?)
View	        shouldRasterizeIOS (generalized support possible?)

Google's certification requirements are changing in August 2019, to require applications to set their target version to be API Level 28. This ticket is intended to capture this change to support any newly released apps beyond August 2019.

See the article here: https://android-developers.googleblog.com/2019/02/expanding-target-api-level-requirements.html

fields.description:
As a software developer using the You.i Engine, I would find it easier to interpret and build standardized tooling upon a commonly used format rather than the proprietary format being used now. Raw profiling data has limited usefulness for easily tracking trends and regressions. 

Our cross platform tool of choice, _easy_profiler_, has a shared file format (described in the attached image): 
 !image-2019-01-17-09-15-22-690.png|thumbnail! 

With the help of additional tooling, it can be converted to JSON via the _profiler_converter_ tool that is built as part of the _easy_profiler_ SDK.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Documentation of the supported elements within the binary format.
* Documentation around any additional information in the cases where our use of the data is a little different than their documented use. For example, the data type should be the same, such as a floating point value, but our value might represent something a little different.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I often what to tune my application by providing platform-specific initialization code for one or more platforms. Preferably through platform specific file extensions -- which is a React-Native mechanism to load JSX source files based on the running platform.

i.e.
https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/platform-specific-code.html#platform-specific-extensions

For example `index.Roku-cloud.js`

For Roku-cloud this provides a clean solution to cases where an app is targeting multiple platforms on the same codebase but requires cloud-specific screen differentiation and API calls.

e.g.
• Screen design will need to be modified for Roku-cloud to some extent (rendering/export limitations). Lists with a single list item template. Screens without background players, etc.
• Use of Roku-cloud specific native modules (exposing Roku API's required for cert and cloud APIs required to make the application function) will naturally need to be called only when running on Roku-cloud.

*Use Case*
* I want to use Facebook's React Native for iOS, Android and Web, and want to use a compatible platform segmentation strategy for non-React Native platforms (e.g: file.platform.js)


*Acceptance Criteria*
* Must support for all platforms.
* Must provide technical documentation around this capability and use cases around how to leverage it.

As a React Native developer, it is difficult to know when properties or components are unsupported. It is especially challenging when these vary from platform to platform. It would be very helpful if the You.i Engine One SDK could provide feedback around unsupported elements that are being used when running my application.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Should provide a yellow box warning, or some other visual indicator, when an unsupported property or component (for the current platform) is being used.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I would like to make use of TypeScript files for the set of JavaScript APIs provided by the You.i Engine One SDK.

Typescript is a growing language that adds optional static type checking to Javascript. It is a superset of Javascript and transpiles to Javascript. Typescript is well suited to development of large applications.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Must provide a TypeScript file against the APIs provided in our SDK.
* Must identify platform exceptions through API documentation in TypeScript.

*Technical Notes*

If a particular library is not written in Typescript, it can still provide a Typescript Definition file to allow its users write in Typescript. Many contributions exist for providing TS type definitions (e.g. [https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/tree/master/types/react-native]) but it is best when a library provides their own definition.

This also help pure Javascript developers because some editors (e.g. Visual Studio Code) have Intellisense capability based on the type definition file available to improve pure Javascript usage as well. (e.g. [https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/languages/javascript\#\_intellisense|https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/languages/javascript#_intellisense])

Along with a type definition for You.i types, we should also consider providing our own version of React Native considering we do not support many of the interface options of React Native.

* Babel 7 now ships with TypeScript support as well.
* Typescript is supported in a lot of editors and IDEs.
* You.i Services Engineering has standardized on Typescript as their language. Peloton has created a TS Type Definition file for You.i Engine and this is now used by Redbox as well. They are also pulling down the community created definition for React Native.

Peloton version is available here : https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/YouiCommunityToolkit/blob/master/types/react-native-youi.d.ts

Redbox is very slightly different : https://github.com/YOU-i-Labs/Redbox/blob/master/react-native-youi.d.ts

fields.description:
As as software developer, I would like a sample demonstrating how to create native modules in my application that call C++ and platform specific functions and vice versa.

*Acceptance Criteria*

* Must work on all platforms
* Must demonstrate native functions being called from JavaScript
* Must demonstrate native functions calling JavaScript
* Must demonstrate Android and iOS platform functions in Java and Swift
* Must make use of a Java library (.jar) (Android only)
* Must make use of an Swift framework (iOS only)
* Must make use of a native C++ library (.a, .so, .dll, or .lib)
* Must review design of sample with UX team and product management before coding begins.

fields.description:
As an application developer, document the process of how native modules can be written, built, and integrated into an application. In general, we need to consider the following integration scenarios:

* C++ source code that needs to be built as a module (ultimately producing a library)
* Platform specific code, such as Obj-C or Swift, that needs to be built as a module (ultimately producing a library)
* A specific example for Android and how to include a .jar library as a native module
* A pre-built native library, such as a .a, .so, or .dylib

The technical "how-to" documentation should cover the following areas (please add if I missed anything):

* How does our process for building native modules differ from Vanilla React Native?
* What are the differences between a native module that gets built as part of an application vs. one that gets built to be shared with others in a repository?
* Are there any technical strategies that make building native modules easier?
* What are the CMake functions needed to integrate the native module into an application?
* What are the classes and types needed when creating a native module and how to use them?
* Show example binding code between the native module and the JavaScript layer

fields.description:
As a application developer, in order to quickly identify where bottlenecks in my application are occurring, we would like to use the SDK with profiling blocks enabled. 

In order to avoid the overhead of profiling, the profiler will aim to provide a complete picture of what's happening in the application, but at a high level. Per-object or multiple-times-per-frame profiling could necessitate a special SDK build configuration.

Acceptance Criteria:
* App developers _must_ be able to use release builds of the engine and easy_profiler to collect metrics
* Debug builds _could_ include profiling information (this information _must_ make obvious that it's captured in debug, e.g. in the block names)
* Information _must_ be available from all target platforms
* Profiling information _should_ be color-coded based on neutral colours for: app hooks, core engine, RN (https://learnui.design/tools/data-color-picker.html)

fields.description:
As a React Native developer using an AE hybrid development model, I should not have to pre-compose my controls to use them as Ref components

For example, if using the Composition source load a CYIPushButton, it should be possible to use "ButtonRef" functionality to control that button. This is currently not possible. As a work-around: the button can be precomposed, then the composition can be loaded, followed by a the use of ButtonRef to get at the button.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Must provide technical documentation around the deprecation of the requirement to pre-compose.
* Must adjust existing API documentation showing the right way to refer to a button when loading from a composition.
* Must be applied to all Ref-able components.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I would like my animations to be driven natively, rather than through JavaScript. This feature can provide more performance options when trying to improve performance in my application.

Reference:
https://facebook.github.io/react-native/blog/2017/02/14/using-native-driver-for-animated

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Must support for all animation and easing types and values where native support is available.
* Must support all engine platforms.
* Must document limitations of support where native support is not available.
* Must validate performance improvements against common usage scenarios.
* Must provide a sample demonstrating common usage scenarios comparing native and non-native animations.
