fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I am trying to bridge an implementation that involves using the React (for web), React Native (for mobile), and React Native (for 10-foot). In the latter case, we are using the You.i Engine. The basic use case is for our web and mobile developers to be able to download and use our abstraction without requiring them to download the full You.i Engine SDK.

We require a package that contains a sub-set of the SDK files offered by the You.i Engine One React Native node package(s). These files are used strictly to satisfy JavaScript require directives and build dependencies. The You.i solution would not be used by external developers, but this dependency package is needed for our solution to work.

REQUIRES: Permission to offer the required source code in a package that can be shared, potentially with people who are not clients of You.i.

*+OR+* REQUIRES: Permission to offer *obfuscated versions* of the required source code in a package that can be shared, potentially with people who are not clients of You.i. Obfuscation of every type of file may not be required.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Separate package that our customers can use to satisfy dependencies for non-You.i developers, when offering a solution involving multi-RN implementations.
* A process of script for automatic generation of the package whenever an official release goes out the door.
* Initial delivery to be tested in conjunction with the client.

fields.description:
h2. Scene tree extension

(Note that this is not tied to the AE workflow)

Having the ability to control the creation of the scene tree, the type of nodes, the import of various resource types, would go a long way to facilitate using the SDK.

h2. Example of implementation
There are a few neat design patterns that could be used to resolve this I might suggest:

- Factory:
    A factory could be passed down to the engine via an API. That factory would handle object types and would have a chance to instantiate different objects. The factory would have an API to comply to. This can include node/view/timeline/other resource types.

- Delegate:
For each object create, a delegate would be called to have a chance to manipulate the node/view/timeline created. This could extend to other resource types if well done.

I'll leave this final implementation details to the SDK developer, but simplicity and extendability is key. Even having the ability to pick a different base scene node and scene view would go a long way to help service developer add features without requiring a new engine drop.

h2. Potential clients
- Twitch
- NGK
- Turner (kids)
- Fox

h2. Extending this for RN
This would go hand in hand with the RN components.

h2. Usage Example

fields.description:
As a software developer using the You.i Engine, I find it difficult to align my development system with the needs of the SDK. There are several dependencies on specific tools and specific versions of those tools, many of which vary from platform to platform. There are also environment variables that may need to be configured, which can impact how the SDK behaves.

As an example of one type of implementation, Google's Flutter CLI has a very convenient doctor sub-command that runs through the user's environment and determines if all the dependencies are met and up to date.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Must account for software dependencies that can vary across platforms.
* Must detect all dependencies and report on report on compatibility based on required versions.
* Must detect obsolete environment variables and report on expected usage.
* Must detect missing or faulty environment variables and report on expected usage.
* Should highlight those that are incompatible (ex: red text).
* Should show the list of dependencies via the command line.
* Should have have the ability to be run manually and the ability to be run from within a user interface (in the case of a visual installer).
* Could have the ability to specify doctor commands on specific platforms (e.g: youi-cli doctor roku)

fields.description:
As a software developer, I find it difficult to build screens that have overlays, pop-ups, or during screen transitions, because I need to trap all input across the entire screen. In most cases, I only want to respond to a couple of events on one or more views, and ignore all of the other inputs.

One example would be a pop-up dialog box that contains one interactive element, such as a cancel button. In this case, I would need to handle the usual events on that button, such as when it has been tapped or if the ESC key has been pressed. However, I also need to ignore all other input until the dialog has been dismissed or until an operation has completed.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Sample demonstrating the use case of a pop-up blocking input from all other controls except for those related to a dismiss button on the dialog.
* API documentation that highlights this use case, explaining the rationale and the methods involved.

* Documentation is updated based on changes to the Engine

fields.description:
As an RN developer, I want the ability to use responsive layout in my screen designs I am creating using JSX only components and properties. A preferred approach is to use a project, such as:

https://github.com/marudy/react-native-responsive-screen

Which allows me to easily specify relative dimensions of components (percentage) against the devices DP  (or DIP) value.

Acceptance Criteria:
* A clear way to communicate ANY limitations of responsive screen functionality
* Documentation to inform developers how to use the third party library, if there are any differences between Vanilla React Native and You.i Engine React Native
* A sample demonstrating the use of react-native-responsive-screen across all supported platforms

fields.description:
As a user I would like to have the latest and greatest toolchain for the PS4 platform.

Description
This ticket captures the research required to validate Engine One officially supporting PlayStation SDK6.
There is some customer\market motivation to Engine realizing this update as SDK v6 includes some includes some cool new developer\profiler tools.

Overview
To test 6.5 PS SDK we'd need to upgrade one of the PS4s to use it
As per the upgrade from v5.0 to v6.0:
{quote}... only have to do is make sure that v6.0 is installed and once it is we just have to change the jenkins file in the uswish repo so it can use the nodes that have v6.0 installed. This applies to the hunter cache and engine build. I think we build castlabs during the same time as the engine.{quote}

* there may be build changes needed to support it (or not)
* need to update the lab machine and a local windows box to use 6.0 PS SDK
* need to go through the tester apps (~60 of them) and samples in both debug and release
* TBD review new development\profile tools
* Creation of a story that outlines the implementation and any associated concerns is the outcome of this SPIKE.

fields.description:
This feature contains the work required to support the Cloud JSX MVP. When preparing our Cloud Solution to support JSX, we would like to:
* Reduce the amount of fragmentation between Cloud and non-Cloud platform for JSX support
* Have props/methods that are visual and not dynamically updated be dynamically update

Acceptance Criteria:
* Documentation is updated to reflect any changes in support of Components/APIs and their props/methods
* All artefacts within this Feature have been completed

fields.description:
We only “officially” support 2.4, but with 2.4 you can’t create Tizen certificates. In my experience, 3.1 works fine, so there should be no issue in upgrading. 

Sales request: 
The developer was saying they wanted to use 3.2, but that they had to downgrade to 2.4 and it messed up his environment. It'd be nice if we could get an official statement by product on 3.2. It's still using Pepper 56, so it should be API compatible.

Attached the CMake error log he was seeing with 3.2. Looks like Pthreads and a `/WX` flag are the culprits.

fields.description:
This story is about implementing support for the SectionList component methods and its properties. A section list is a performant interface for rendering sectioned lists. This is a convenience wrapper around _VirtualizedList_, and thus inherits its props (as well as those of _ScrollView_.

One common use case is to show a list with items sorted based on category, or in alphabetical order, with each result being contained within a section of the list, such as an ordered genre list. With the current list implementation, there is no easy way to accomplish these common use cases.

Reference: https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/sectionlist.html

*Component Properties*
* sections
* initialNumToRender
* keyExtractor
* renderItem
* onEndReached
* extraData
* ItemSeparatorComponent
* inverted
* ListFooterComponent
* -legacyImplementation-
* ListEmptyComponent
* onEndReachedThreshold
* onRefresh
* onViewableItemsChanged
* refreshing
* removeClippedSubviews
* ListHeaderComponent
* renderSectionFooter
* renderSectionHeader
* SectionSeparatorComponent
* stickySectionHeadersEnabled

*Methods*
* scrollToLocation
* -recordInteraction-
* flashScrollIndicators

*Acceptance Criteria*
* We are not supporting any methods or component and style properties that have been struck out.
* Updated documentation on support for the Component and props that are implemented as part of the work
* Any props that cannot be implemented will have stories created and split from this PM ticket.
* Working sample or demonstration of a Section List in the TestApp

fields.description:
This request to build on the current solution of bringing in embedded frameworks to:

(1) place the framework in `thirdparty/ios/EmbeddedFrameworks/`
(2) call `yi_configure_framework` with location and signing information from your platform specific cmake.

The request is to allow a Podfile to pull down the file, and have the above automatically happen without intervention. 

In meantime I have instructed how they could be wired together using script, cmake, fastlane, but an official recommendation or process would be nice.

fields.description:
As an application developer handling web requests, I often have the need to handle and manage cookies for my application in addition making HTTP requests and handling responses.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Ability to retrieve cookies out of the cookie store with documentation around the caveats if a shared cookie store is being used.
* Ability to set cookies on the HTTP request.
* Ability to clear cookies and any documentation around the caveats.
* Cross platform documentation on the limitations or fragmentation of cookie management.
* Technical documentation on how the cookie management solution works.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I would like more information about the device so that can be used for analytics.

-`deviceVersion` - No equivalent in the C++ API.-
`deviceManufacturer` - ex. “Sony”, we can infer it through platform constant (with exception of AndroidTV), but would be good also to have it
`deviceModel` - ex. “BRAVIA 4K GB”, in c++ there is GetDeviceModel() in YiDeviceInformationBridge.h but not in js
`deviceName` - ex. “BRAVIA_ATV2”, didn’t find equivalent in c++ API
`deviceType` - ex. “AndroidTV” in c++ there is GetDeviceType() in YiDeviceTypeBridge.h but not in js

*Acceptance Criteria*
* API support for all supported platforms
* API should return an empty string for platforms that do not provide a value

fields.description:
As a product manager, I find application stores update cycles to be long and expensive. I want to be able to make changes to my JavaScript code to update my application, without having to go through the application certification process.


*Reference*
There are existing services that provide a solution. Below is Microsoft Code Push, which supporting could be the solution to the user story above.

* https://microsoft.github.io/code-push/

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Published investigation results on how or if a service can be used with assets, such as images. Knowledge around the services compatibility with AE assets is required.
* Published investigation results on how or if a service can be used native code.
* Published investigation results around how versioning is handled.

fields.description:
As a software developer using either the C++ or React Native SDKs, I often find the need to provide seamless playback of assets. For example, playing an ad at scheduled times during a show, and then returning to that show without long buffering cycles in-between each transition.

* https://developer.apple.com/documentation/avfoundation/avqueueplayer
* https://developer.android.com/about/versions/android-4.1#Gapless /
* https://google.github.io/ExoPlayer/doc/reference/com/google/android/exoplayer2/source/ConcatenatingMediaSource.html

*Acceptance Criteria*
* API support in C++ and React Native
* New or modified video player sample that allows toggling the gapless support; playback should use two freely available independent streams to demonstrate.
* DRM support must be compatible with the solution

fields.description:
Performance is one of the key themes around our React Native initiative. Our JavaScript interpreter is currently running on the main thread for our application; this main thread is also the rendering thread. As a result, application developers will experience visual aberrations, such as visual stuttering, in their application. This is especially noticeable on CPU bound platforms, such as Blue Sky or lower end Amazon Fire TV devices.

This story is about moving the JavaScript interpreter to its own thread, separate from our application thread.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Publishable metrics on performance gains or losses on Blue Sky, Amazon Fire, and Samsung Tizen.
* Performance testing against a real world application

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I find it difficult to transition and reason about the layout system used in the engine and After Effects. The layout capabilities do not match those used by React Native. There is very little cooperation between the two implementations which makes it difficult to reason about how to achieve a design. The most challenging problems facing a developer trying to achieve a particular design are listed below:

* Very little support of After Effects layout attributes in React Native (things get ignored or overridden)
* No support of React Native layout attributes against You.i Ref components
* Differences in capabilities between the two systems

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Support within After Effects for the Flexbox layout
* Deprecation of obsolete layout components within the SDK
* Updated documentation around the use of the After Effects component
* Updating existing samples in React Native to use the new component
* Updating existing samples in the C++ SDK to use the new component
* A new sample demonstrating the capabilities and compatibility between React Native and After Effects

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I find it difficult to reason about screens built in After Effects. The hierarchal model is difficult to reason about and is not the model I am used to dealing with in Android or iOS. There are also performance benefits to using a constraint based layout system that I want to take advantage of.

Constraint based layouts should solve screen layout size problems against the following external / internal changes:
* The user resizes the window (desktop only).
* The user enters or leaves a Split View on iOS or via Split Screen Mode on Android.
* The device rotates (mobile only).
* The active call, audio recording bars, or status bars appear or disappear (mobile only).
* Support different screen sizes.
* The content displayed by the application changes.
* The application supports internationalization.
* The application is responding to requests for text size changes (accessibility).

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Engage with development team to identify features that have the most value and partition the feature delivery in phases.
* Review of constraint rules needed with the relevant stake holders to accommodate the above change scenarios before the features have been built.
* Constraint rules must work on all supported platforms, but not all change scenarios need to be supported on all platforms.
* Constraint rules must be accessible from within the After Effects plug-in.
* Sample demonstrating all available constraint rules, but not all change scenarios.
* Technical documentation describing constraint rules available, constraint rule combinations, and how to achieve non-ambiguous layouts.

fields.description:
As a React Native developer building screen designs, I cannot a build a design that works well across all of the screens I need to support. The scaling that I see across devices is inconsistent and does not match the behaviour I see when building against Vanilla RN.

If I choose the hybrid model, then I need to use the workflow which does not support device independent units, so the scale of my designs do not match that I would get if I used pure JSX. If I choose pure JSX, then the result does not match what I get with Vanilla React Native.

*Technical Reference*
* https://developer.android.com/training/multiscreen/screendensities
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Device-independent_pixel

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Support for specifying units in the After Effects workflow, or a change in the default unit (DIP rather than pixel)
* Support for DIP values in JSX
* No support needed for other metric units such as CM, MM, INCH, etc.
* No API support needed for DIP units
* Updated documentation around our support for it

fields.description:
As a C++ developer, I find the CYIFocusZoneView class to be very useful. This feature is about building a sample demonstrating one or more custom focus behaviours, and documenting the key usage patterns surrounding this class.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Must include a sample demonstrating at least one custom focus behaviour, making use of the CYIFocusZoneView class.
* Must include technical documentation around typical use cases and best practices involving the CYIFocusZoneView class.
* Must work on all supported platforms

fields.description:
As a React Native developer who is not using the After Effects workflow for screen building, I would like a sample that can be used to learn from and evaluate the JSX support in You.i Engine One.

The goal of this ticket is to take the IBC demo/Orion work and to convert any After Effects assets into JSX components.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Recreate the existing IBC demo/Orion work using only JSX components.
* Must adjust to screen sizes using layout facilities of React Native.
* Must support "responsive layout" (ex: https://youilabs.atlassian.net/browse/RN-1564)
* Must work on all supported platforms. (including mobile touch events and rotation)
* Updated documentation on how to build the JSX sample application

fields.description:
As a React Native developer, I would like access to a DRM sample that demonstrates:

* Custom DRM certificate
* Uses a DRM method when available

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Pseudo-code that demonstrates how a certificate could be provided is acceptable
* Works on at least one platform that supports one of our supported DRM methods
* Defaults to playing un-protected video on the other platforms where DRM is not being used
* Should play content full screen after launching with a "play video" button
* Supports playing, pausing, and reloading video; the reload option should completely shut down the player and start it back up again.

fields.description:
We want to upgrade to version 0.57 of React Native in preparation for 0.58 and in response to repeated customer requests around access to additional tooling possibilities.

0.57 is seen as a LTS (long time support) release by Facebook. Considering the big changes coming to 0.58 and beyond, it is critical for us to move to a later version.

*Acceptance Criteria*
* Evaluation and discussion of impact around moving to 0.57 with the PM team
* Evaluation and discussion of impact around moving to 0.58 with the PM team
* Upgrade our base version of React Native to 0.57
* Technical documentation around the impact of the move (delivered as part of the assessment)
